The elemental composition and surface analysis of the N-CDs, NS-CDs, and NB-CDs are determined using XPS spectroscopy. Fig. 3
                        a shows the full scan of N-CDs, NS-CDs, and NB-CDs confirming the major compositions of carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, sulfur, and boron. After deconvolution, the C1s spectrum of N-CDs (Fig. 3b) displays five predominant peaks at 284.4, 284.9, 285.4, 286.4, and 288.9 eV, which correspond to CC, CC, CN, CO, and CO bonds, respectively [36]. The high resolution of the N1s XPS spectra deconvoluted into two peaks at 399.7 eV and 400.1 eV, ascribed to CN or CN and CNC bonds, respectively [37]. Similarly, the deconvoluted O1s spectrum illustrates four peaks at 532, 532.4, 533.3, and 533.9 eV, which are assigned to CO, CO, OCOH, and OH, respectively, as illustrated in Fig. 3b. Furthermore, the elemental composition ratio showed (Table 1
                        ) that N-CDs contained carbon (83.74 %), oxygen (15.42 %), and nitrogen (0.84 %).
